";; appendix-07-norman-mclaren.slat
;; Book of Motion — Appendix 7: Norman McLaren and Direct Animation
;; Written 2026-07-13. Author: Lacuna Labs Engineering.
;; Real subject: Norman McLaren (1914-1987), Scottish-Canadian animator.
;; Sources: Terence Dobson, The Film Work of Norman McLaren (John Libbey, 2007);
;; National Film Board of Canada archives.

(appendix
  :book \"book-of-motion\"
  :number 7
  :title \"Norman McLaren and Direct Animation\"
  :short-title \"norman-mclaren\"
  :estimated-words 1300
  :subject-verified \"Norman McLaren, born 11 April 1914, Stirling, Scotland; died 27 January 1987, Montreal. Animator, primarily associated with the National Film Board of Canada from 1941.\"
  :philosopher-weave (peirce sartre aristotle)

  :prose
\"Norman McLaren, working at the National Film Board of Canada from 1941 until his retirement in 1983, developed a body of experimental animation that was unlike any other in the medium. He worked on individual sequences for years, exploring specific technical questions — what happens if you scratch the emulsion of the film directly? what happens if you photograph a live actor one frame at a time and let them move slightly between frames? what happens if you overlay two frames of dancing at different speeds? His films are meditations on the physical medium of animation.

McLaren was not concerned with characters, or with narrative in the conventional sense. He was concerned with what animation *is* — with the direct relationship between the physical film strip and the perceived motion. His work is closer to abstract art or experimental music than to storytelling animation.

# Direct animation

McLaren's earliest signature technique was *direct animation* — drawing or scratching directly onto the celluloid of the film strip. In the 1940s and 1950s, he made a series of films (*Dots*, 1940; *Loops*, 1940; *Boogie Doodle*, 1941; *Fiddle-de-dee*, 1947) in which every frame was a scratch or dab of paint on the film itself. When the film was projected, the marks appeared as moving abstract shapes, synchronized to music.

This technique has an unusual philosophical property. In conventional animation, drawings are photographed frame by frame; the film is a record of a series of drawings. In direct animation, the film *is* the drawing. There is no separation between the physical film strip and the animated image. What the projector shows is exactly what McLaren scratched.

# Neighbours (1952)

McLaren's *Neighbours* — an 8-minute short from 1952 — used a technique called *pixilation* to animate live actors as if they were animated puppets. Two neighbors, played by live actors, are photographed frame by frame; between frames, they move slightly, so when the film is projected the actors appear to move in unnatural, jerky, staccato motion.

The film's premise: two neighbors sit peacefully in their yards until a flower grows between them. Both want the flower. They fight over it. The fight escalates. By the end of the film, both are dead and the flower is destroyed.

Neighbours won an Academy Award for Best Documentary Short (1952 — categorization was contested but the film received the honor). It is a political allegory produced during the Korean War and remains one of the most striking anti-war statements in the medium.

The pixilation technique gave the actors an unheimlich, animated quality. They were unmistakably real people, but they moved as animated figures. This blurring — human bodies in animated time — produced a specific unsettling effect that McLaren returned to in subsequent films.

# Pas de deux (1968)

*Pas de deux* is a ten-minute film in which two ballet dancers (Margaret Mercier and Vincent Warren) perform a duet in silhouette against a black background. McLaren photographed the dance normally, but he then processed the film so that each moment of the dance was overlaid with images of the dancers' positions from several frames earlier and later. The result is that a single dancer, at any moment, appears as multiple overlapping ghost-images of herself — the trailing echoes of her past positions and the pre-echoes of her future ones.

The effect is astonishing. A dancer performing a lift is preceded and followed by multiple translucent versions of herself, each in a slightly different position. When she moves, all her ghosts move with her, each with its own lag or lead. The film is like watching a dance while also seeing every phase of its motion trailing behind and reaching ahead.

*Pas de deux* is often shown to animation students as an example of what can be done at the boundary between live-action and animated technique. It uses live dance as its material but treats time itself as animation.

# What McLaren's work teaches

McLaren teaches that animation is a medium of *time manipulation*. The frame is not just a drawing to be advanced twenty-four times a second; the frame is a moment that can be scratched, overlaid, delayed, doubled, and combined with adjacent moments to produce effects that only animation can produce.

For animators working with digital tools today, McLaren's work is a reminder that the *physical properties of the medium* — whatever the current medium is — are themselves expressive material. In McLaren's era, the physical medium was 35mm film, and he scratched it, painted on it, exposed it multiple times. Today the physical medium is often digital pixels, layers, and shaders, and the same experimental spirit applies: what happens if you manipulate the digital medium directly? What can be shown by working *with the medium* rather than through it?

McLaren's technical papers, published as internal National Film Board documents in the 1950s and 1960s, are still studied by experimental animators. His combination of technical curiosity and aesthetic seriousness set a standard that later independent animators — the Quay Brothers, Jan Švankmajer, Jodie Mack — have continued in their different ways.

# What we can do in Scheme

A small demonstration of overlaid-time animation (the *Pas de deux* trick).

```scheme
;; Given a sequence of frames, produce a new sequence where each frame is
;; overlaid with the frames a few positions before and after.

(define (overlaid-frame all-frames index)
  (let* ((n (length all-frames))
         (indices (list (max 0 (- index 6))
                        (max 0 (- index 3))
                        index
                        (min (- n 1) (+ index 3))
                        (min (- n 1) (+ index 6))))
         (frames (map (lambda (i) (list-ref all-frames i)) indices))
         (alphas '(0.2 0.4 1.0 0.4 0.2)))
    (world/reset!)
    (for-each
      (lambda (frame alpha)
        (world/place-frame frame :alpha alpha))
      frames alphas)
    (world/render!)))

(define (overlaid-time-animation frames)
  (transport/fps 24)
  (for-each
    (lambda (i)
      (overlaid-frame frames i)
      (world/wait (/ 1.0 24.0)))
    (range 0 (length frames))))
```

Each frame in the output is the center frame at full opacity, overlaid with the frames 3 and 6 positions before and after at reduced opacity. When the animation plays, the current moment is always visible clearly, but ghostly versions of adjacent moments trail behind and lead ahead. This is a Scheme approximation of McLaren's technique.

The result would be that any motion in the original animation — a walk, a jump, a wave — would appear surrounded by translucent echoes of itself. Time becomes visible.

# Recommended viewing

*Neighbours* (1952). Available from the National Film Board of Canada online archive.

*Pas de deux* (1968). Also available from NFB online.

*Blinkity Blank* (1955). Direct animation scratched onto film.

*A Chairy Tale* (1957). Live-action pixilation, this time with a chair as the antagonist.

Many of McLaren's films are freely viewable at nfb.ca (National Film Board of Canada archive).

# Sources cited

Terence Dobson, *The Film Work of Norman McLaren* (John Libbey Publishing, 2007). Standard critical monograph.

National Film Board of Canada, Norman McLaren archive. Includes technical notes, correspondence, and films.

Donald McWilliams, ed., *Norman McLaren: On the Creative Process* (National Film Board of Canada, 1991). Collection of McLaren's own writings on his technique.\"

  :notes
\"McLaren's biographical dates (1914-1987) and NFB tenure (1941-1983) are standard and verifiable. All named films (Dots, Loops, Boogie Doodle, Fiddle-de-dee, Neighbours, Pas de deux, Blinkity Blank, A Chairy Tale) exist and are documented. Neighbours won an Academy Award in 1953 for the 1952 film year — the categorization confusion is noted honestly. NFB online archive is real and does host these films for public viewing.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Peirce: direct animation as pure index — the scratches on the film ARE the physical trace of the animator's hand; there is no representation-of, only the mark itself.
Sartre: McLaren's practice as commitment to a specific medium — the animator IS what they do to the film strip.
Aristotle: time-manipulation as the animator's true material — animation is the shape of an action through time, and McLaren treated the time-shape as the primary compositional element.\"

  :tie-forward
\"The final appendix will look at contemporary independent animation and where the medium is going.\")
")
